Momordica charantia

L. (
Cucurbitaceae
), also known as an edible bitter melon (English), goya (
Japan
), or kugua (Chinese area), originating in 
India
, is now widely cultivated in Asia, South America, and Africa. 

M. charantia

has been used as an herbal medicine for hundreds of years to treat cough, liver heating, stomachic complaints, anthelmintic, and diabetes-related diseases (

; 

). Previous pharmacological investigations of 

M. charantia

have revealed various biological activities, such as antiviral (

; 

; 

), antitumor (

; 

; 

), antiulcer (

), antidiabetic (

; 

; 

), anti-obesity (

; 

), antibacterial (

), and anti-inflammatory (

; 

; 

) activity.

Our previous study focused on fruits and isolated cucurbitane-type triterpenoids and their glycosides with promising anti-inflammatory, antidiabetic, and cytotoxic activities (
;
;
). In preliminary bioassay studies on the vines of wild
M. charantia
, the CHCl 3 fraction from the 95% EtOH extract showed an anti-inflammatory effect at a concentration of 10 μg/mL (IC 50 = 19.85 μg/mL) by inhibiting nitric oxide (NO) production in LPS-stimulated RAW264.7 macrophage cells. In addition, the fraction also exhibited cytotoxicity against WiDr, Hep-2, HEp-G2, and MCF-7 cancer cells with IC 50 values of 28.54, 24.12, 22.96, and 31.57 μg/mL, respectively.

Some pharmacological reports have shown that the isolated components and aqueous extracts from 

M. charantia

exert hypoglycemic effects by elevating GLP-1 secretion (

; 

). Glucagon-like peptide 1 (GLP-1) has been suggested to be an important antidiabetic incretin hormone that is secreted from intestinal L cells. GLP-1 possesses a glucose-dependent insulin stimulatory effect, boosts β- cell function, and suppresses hepatic glucose production and glucagon secretion (

; 

). Since GLP-1 is rapidly degraded by dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DDP4) 
in vivo
, generating stable DPP4-resistant GLP-1 analogs or small molecule-based DPP4 inhibitors has become a major strategy for the treatment of diabetes (

; 

). However, modulation of endogenous GLP-1 levels by using agents that stimulate intestinal GLP-1 secretion has also gradually gained more attention (

; 

). In the present study, the GLP-1 secretory effect of isolated cucurbitanes was evaluated in a murine intestinal secretin tumor cell line (STC-1). The anti-NO production and cytotoxic activities of these compounds are also reported herein.

Compound 1 , white amorphous powder ([ α ] 25D 67, MeOH), has a molecular formula of C 41 H 64 O 12 as derived from its HRESIMS at m/z 771.4291 ([M+Na] + , calcd. for C 41 H 64 O 12 Na, 771.4295). The IR spectrum displayed the absorptions of hydroxyl ( 3440 cm 1 ), carbonyl (1752 and 1732 cm 1 ), and olefinic (1642 and 1446 cm 1 ) functional groups. The 13 C- and DEPT NMR spectra of compound 1 ( Table 1 ) revealed the existence of two ester carbonyls ( δ C 167.5 and 166.8), four olefinic carbons ( δ C 129.1, 131.6, 132.2, and 132.8), two acetal carbons ( δ C 104.2 and 112.3), one oxygenated quaternary carbon ( δ C 84.0), four other quaternary carbons ( δ C 37.8, 45.4, 48.1, and 48.3), six oxygenated methines ( δ C 71.8, 75.3, 75.6, 78.2, 78.3, and 78.9), one oxygenated methylene ( δ C 62.9), eight methylenes ( δ C 18.4, 23.2, 25.1, 28.2, 30.8, 33.8, 42.2, and 43.8), two methoxyls ( δ C 52.57 and 33.8), seven methyls ( δ C 14.8, 18.2, 19.4, 19.9, 20.0, 24.2, and 25.8), and four methines ( δC 32.6, 41.5, 42.1, 51.4). The 1 H-NMR spectrum of 1 ( Table 2 ) also clearly showed signals for six singlets of methyl ( δ H 0.86, 0.90, 0.92, 1.18, 1.66, and 1.75), a doublet of methyl [ δ H 1.17 (d, J =6.0 Hz)], two methoxyls ( δ H 3.49 and 3.69), eight oxymethine protons ( δ H 3.88, 4.00, 4.20, 4.22, 4.77, 4.91, 4.93, and 4.95), one oxymethylene proton [ δ H 4.32 (dd, J = 11.0, 4.0 Hz) and 4.46 (br d, J = 11.0 Hz)], and three olefinic protons [ δ H 5.59 (dd, J =3.5, 10.0 Hz), 5.61 (br d, J =8.0 Hz), and 6.10 (br d, J = 9.5 Hz)]. The above 1 H and 13 C-NMR evidence suggested that compound 1 possessed a 5,19-epoxycucurbitane-type triterpene skeleton with a sugar moiety and malonyl group and was similar to taikuguasin D isolated from the fruits of
M. charantia
in a previous report (
). The planar structure of 1 was further established by 1 H– 1 H COSY and HMBC experiments ( Fig. 2A ). The malonyl group was assigned at C-3 based on the HMBC correlation between H-3 ( δ H 4.38) and C-1’ ( δ C 166.8). The HMBC correlations of two methoxyl groups ( δ H 3.69 and 3.49) with δ C 167.5 and 112.3, respectively, suggested that methoxyl groups were linked at C-3 ′ and C-19. Moreover, the sugar moiety at C-23 was clearly determined by the COSY correlations (Glc-1/Glc-2/Glc-3/Glc-4/Glc-5/Glc-6) and HMBC correlations between Glc-1 [ δ H 4.95 (d, J = 8.0 Hz)] and C-23 ( δ C 75.3). The hexose sugar moiety was confirmed as β -glucose by the coupling constant of Glc-1, and the D-form was identified by acid hydrolysis of 1 (
).
